 METHODOLOGY

Phase 1: Server Setup (Kali Linux)

The first step was preparing the Kali Linux machine to host the Wazuh manager.

BASH
Step 1: Update the system
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

Step 2: Install curl
sudo apt install curl -y

Step 3: Download and install Wazuh manager
curl -sO https://packages.wazuh.com/4.x/wazuh-install.sh
sudo bash ./wazuh-install.sh -a


After installation, Wazuh automatically generated login credentials (username and password). These were used to access the Wazuh dashboard via the server's local IP address in a browser:

- https://[SERVER-IP]


Phase 2: Agent Enrollment (Ubuntu)

From the Wazuh dashboard on the server, I navigated to Deploy Agent and configured the following:

| Field           | Value Selected          |
|-----------------|-------------------------|
| Package Type    | DEB                     |
| Architecture    | AMD64                   |
| Server Address  | [Kali Linux local IP]   |
| Agent Name      | [Custom label for Ubuntu VM] |

The dashboard generated a one-line enrollment script. This was executed on the Ubuntu machine:

BASH
Script generated by Wazuh dashboard, run on Ubuntu agent
sudo WAZUH_MANAGER='[SERVER-IP]' WAZUH_AGENT_NAME='[AGENT-NAME]' \
  apt-get install wazuh-agent

## Enable and start the agent service
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable wazuh-agent
sudo systemctl start wazuh-agent


After execution, the Ubuntu agent appeared as Active on the Wazuh dashboard — confirming a successful connection between endpoint and server.



Phase 3: VirusTotal Integration

To enable malware hash lookups on detected files, I integrated the VirusTotal API into the Wazuh manager configuration.

Process:
1. Created a free VirusTotal account at [virustotal.com](https://virustotal.com) and retrieved the API key.
2. Edited the Wazuh manager configuration file on Kali:

```bash
sudo nano /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf
```

3. Added the following integration block inside `<ossec_config>`:

```xml
<integration>
  <name>virustotal</name>
  <api_key>YOUR_VIRUSTOTAL_API_KEY</api_key>
  <rule_id>550, 554</rule_id>
  <alert_format>json</alert_format>
</integration>
```

How it works: When Wazuh's File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) detects a new or modified file, it extracts the file hash and sends it to VirusTotal. VirusTotal cross-references it against 70+ antivirus engines and returns a verdict — flagging it as clean or malicious, with a direct link to the full scan report.

Phase 4: Real-Time File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) Configuration

I configured Wazuh to monitor the file system in real-time, with a 2-minute scan frequency.

**File edited:** `/var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf` (on Wazuh server)

```xml
<syscheck>

  <!-- Changed from default (every 12 hours) to 2 minutes (120 seconds) -->
  <frequency>120</frequency>

  <!-- Enable real-time monitoring on critical directories -->
  <directories realtime="yes">/root</directories>
  <directories realtime="yes">/home</directories>
  <directories realtime="yes">/tmp</directories>

</syscheck>
```

Note: `frequency` is measured in seconds. Default is 43200 (12 hours). Setting it to 120 enables near-immediate detection of file changes during testing.

After editing, the Wazuh manager was restarted to apply changes:

```bash
sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager
```

