Phase 5: Malware Simulation — EICAR Test File

To validate the detection pipeline, I downloaded the EICAR test file — a universally recognized, harmless malware simulation string — to the Ubuntu agent:

```bash
curl -Lo /root/eicar.com https://secure.eicar.org/eicar.com
```

What happened:
- Wazuh FIM detected the new file in `/root` immediately (real-time mode active)
- The file hash was sent to VirusTotal via the integration
- An alert fired on the Wazuh dashboard, flagging the file as malicious
- The alert included a direct VirusTotal link with the full scan verdict

This confirmed the full detection chain was functioning: **endpoint → file change → hash lookup → threat alert.**


Phase 6: Active Response — Automated Threat Removal

To close the loop from detection to remediation, I built an automated active response that removes malicious files without manual intervention.

Step 1: Write the removal script (on Ubuntu agent)

```bash
sudo nano /var/ossec/active-response/bin/remove-threat.sh
```

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# remove-threat.sh
# Active response script: removes files flagged as malicious by Wazuh + VirusTotal

LOCAL=`dirname $0`
cd $LOCAL
cd ../

PWD=`pwd`

read INPUT_JSON
FILENAME=$(echo $INPUT_JSON | python3 -c 'import sys, json; data = json.load(sys.stdin); print(data["parameters"]["alert"]["syscheck"]["path"])')

# Log the action
echo "$(date '+%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S') Removing threat: $FILENAME" >> ${PWD}/logs/active-responses.log

# Remove the malicious file
rm -f "$FILENAME"

if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
  echo "$(date '+%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S') Successfully removed: $FILENAME" >> ${PWD}/logs/active-responses.log
else
  echo "$(date '+%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S') Failed to remove: $FILENAME" >> ${PWD}/logs/active-responses.log
fi
```

Step 2: Set permissions

```bash
Make executable
sudo chmod 750 /var/ossec/active-response/bin/remove-threat.sh

Set correct ownership
sudo chown root:wazuh /var/ossec/active-response/bin/remove-threat.sh
```

Step 3: Register the command and active response in `ossec.conf` (Wazuh server)

```xml
<!-- Define the command -->
<command>
  <name>remove-threat</name>
  <executable>remove-threat.sh</executable>
  <timeout_allowed>no</timeout_allowed>
</command>

<!-- Define the active response trigger -->
<active-response>
  <command>remove-threat</command>
  <location>local</location>
  <rules_id>87105</rules_id>
</active-response>
```

Rule 87105: is the Wazuh rule ID that fires when VirusTotal returns a positive malware verdict. Binding the active response to this rule ensures the removal script only triggers on confirmed threats.

After saving, the manager was restarted:

```bash
sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager
```

End-to-end flow confirmed:
`File dropped → FIM detects → VirusTotal flags → Rule 87105 fires → remove-threat.sh executes → file deleted automatically`

